<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Without fear of retribution from the Government. You can't possibly think that you have the right to say whatever you want, where ever you want without fear of retribution.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>How would you like it if you started to receive death threath because you think it was ok for those people to burn the dixie chick CD? I bet you would sing a very different song. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
1. The likelyhood of my expressing that this behaivor is ok and it resulting in death threats is so remote that I would not fear for it happening. The professor that I pointed out was threatened by citizens, not the government. Furthermore, its is likely to foresee the reaction that he got considering the mood of the country at the time he made the remarks. I am not condoning the death threats made to the guy. I hope they are tracking those people down and charging them with crimes. But I laugh my ass off thinking that the reaction came as a surprise to the guy. He publicly states that he hopes our troops get slaughtered and dragged through the streets like dead animals on a parade. Come on, what level of education do you need to realize that this is going to piss some people off?<br>
<br>
2. No one prevented him from making the statement, or threatened him with legal action if he did make the statement. He was not arrested for espousing an unpopular sentiment. Students who were enrolled in his classes also planned a boycot of his classes because of his statements. They were not forced to attend his class, they were afforded the 'right' not to go. No ones free speech was violated. <br>
<br>
3. What I find amusing is that one person's 'free speech' caused a reaction in another form of 'free speech' and yet one is seen as inherently good and the other 'inherently' bad (ie the burning of the CD's). The argument that was made was that free speech should be protected, and yet they use as an example a form of expressing free speech as the result we wish to avoid. You can't have it both ways. Just because someone is anti-war or against the policy of the current administration it doesn't make everything they say or do <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>MORE</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> worthwhile free speech than someone who supports the government. They are the <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>same</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> thing. If you can't see that then you miss the entire point of free speech and are in the same boat as those who say &quot;Free speech is for those who think like us.&quot;  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#242422><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub40.ezboard.com/bthesaryrntavern.showUserPublicProfile?gid=gallaorn>Gallaorn</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style='color:orange;'>Tavern Resident</span></span><br>  Posts: 1123<br> <font color=#6FB8DD>(5/14/03 1:48 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub40.ezboard.com/fthesaryrntavernthefurnace.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3251.topic&index=42>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> bah you get the point no subject</span><hr size=1> Retribution from gov't or from an individual citizen or a group of them is the same thing in the end. Dead is dead it doesnt matter who killed you really.<br>
<br>
I am not arguing that the professor was smart or stupid, and i obviously dont agree with his point of view however as long as he doesnt do anything to kill soldiers he is entitile to his opinions ans shouldnt lose his jobs or receive death threat because of it.<br>
<br>
I guess you can pass the CD burning as free speech as in a demonstration but it imply violence and that is unacceptable. You can disagree and think gwb is a swell guy, you can stop buying their CD if you got offended thats your right. However you should not be allowed to make their life hell for the sole reason that you dont agree with them.<br>
<br>
&lt;&lt;The likelyhood of my expressing that this behaivor is ok and it resulting in death threats is so remote that I would not fear for it happening&gt;&gt;<br>
<br>
So in short as long as you express popular opinions you are ok. And thats the entire point really, you shouldnt live in fear of voicing unpopular opinion is a free society built on free speech. I think it is time we live up to the same standard we impose on our governement, if they are not allowed retribution on individuals for voicing unpopular opinions why should we be able to do it in impunity?<br>
